{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645379"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:17:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:17:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18111"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18111"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.15,0.15,0.35,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10825"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78289"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10825","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10825"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18111"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63684"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7231"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25195"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25198"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78289"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe triangular interval is an anatomical space located in the posterior aspect of the shoulder region. It is bordered by the teres major muscle, the long head of the triceps brachii muscle, and the humerus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves is found in this interval?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Axillary","Suprascapular","Dorsal scapular","Radial","Ulnar"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eradial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is found in the triangular interval. This space is located in the posterior aspect of the shoulder region and is bordered by the teres major muscle, the long head of the triceps brachii muscle, and the humerus. The radial nerve passes through this interval to innervate the posterior compartment of the arm and forearm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAxillary nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This nerve passes through the quadrangular space, not the triangular interval\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuprascapular nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This nerve passes through the suprascapular notch, not the triangular interval\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDorsal scapular nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This nerve innervates the rhomboid muscles and does not pass through the triangular interval\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUlnar nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This nerve travels along the medial aspect of the arm and does not pass through the triangular interval\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The radial nerve is located in the triangular interval, a space in the posterior aspect of the shoulder region.","The triangular interval is bordered by the teres major muscle, the long head of the triceps brachii muscle, and the humerus.","The radial nerve is responsible for innervating the posterior compartment of the arm and forearm."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbo